## 1) Add a top-bar link: “API Keys” → modal for entering keys

### UX requirements
- Add a link/button in the top navigation/header: **“API Keys”**.
- Clicking opens a modal with:
  - A list of supported APIs (one input per API key).
  - “Save” and “Cancel/Close” actions.
  - Optional “Show/Hide” toggle for each key.
  - Optional “Test” button per provider (if you have a lightweight validation endpoint).

### Security/storage recommendation
- **Best practice:** store keys server-side (encrypted at rest) and associate with a user/session.
- If this is a local-only tool or no backend exists:
  - Store in **memory** for the session, or
  - Store in `localStorage` **only if you accept the risk** (keys can be read by any JS running on the page).

A pragmatic compromise:
- Default to **in-memory**.
- Provide an opt-in checkbox: “Remember on this device (stores in localStorage)”.

### Data model
Create a single object keyed by provider name:
```js
const apiKeys = {
  openai: "",
  anthropic: "",
  google: "",
  // add others supported by the project
};
```

### Modal content (suggested)
- Title: **API Keys**
- Short note: “Keys are used to call external APIs. Keep them private.”
- Inputs:
  - OpenAI API Key
  - Anthropic API Key
  - Google (Gemini) API Key
  - Any other providers your project supports
- Buttons:
  - **Save** (persist to chosen storage)
  - **Close**
  - Optional: **Clear saved keys**

### Minimal plain-HTML example (modal)
You can adapt this to your component system.

**Header links:**
```html
<nav class="topbar">
  <a href="#" id="apiKeysLink">API Keys</a>
  <a href="#" id="aboutLink">About</a>
</nav>
```

**Modal markup (API Keys):**
```html
<dialog id="apiKeysDialog">
  <form method="dialog" id="apiKeysForm">
    <h2>API Keys</h2>
    <p>Enter your keys for the providers you use. Keep them private.</p>

    <label>
      OpenAI API Key
      <input name="openai" type="password" autocomplete="off" placeholder="sk-..." />
    </label>

    <label>
      Anthropic API Key
      <input name="anthropic" type="password" autocomplete="off" placeholder="..." />
    </label>

    <label>
      Google (Gemini) API Key
      <input name="google" type="password" autocomplete="off" placeholder="..." />
    </label>

    <label style="display:flex; gap:.5rem; align-items:center; margin-top:1rem;">
      <input type="checkbox" name="remember" />
      Remember on this device (stores in localStorage)
    </label>

    <menu style="display:flex; gap:.5rem; justify-content:flex-end; margin-top:1rem;">
      <button value="cancel">Close</button>
      <button id="saveApiKeysBtn" value="default">Save</button>
    </menu>
  </form>
</dialog>
```

**JS wiring + storage:**
```js
const apiKeysLink = document.getElementById('apiKeysLink');
const apiKeysDialog = document.getElementById('apiKeysDialog');
const apiKeysForm = document.getElementById('apiKeysForm');

const STORAGE_KEY = 'codex_manager_api_keys';

function loadKeys() {
  try {
    return JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem(STORAGE_KEY) || '{}');
  } catch {
    return {};
  }
}

function fillFormFromStorage() {
  const saved = loadKeys();
  for (const name of ['openai', 'anthropic', 'google']) {
    if (saved[name]) apiKeysForm.elements[name].value = saved[name];
  }
}

apiKeysLink.addEventListener('click', (e) => {
  e.preventDefault();
  fillFormFromStorage();
  apiKeysDialog.showModal();
});

apiKeysForm.addEventListener('submit', (e) => {
  e.preventDefault();

  const data = new FormData(apiKeysForm);
  const keys = {
    openai: String(data.get('openai') || ''),
    anthropic: String(data.get('anthropic') || ''),
    google: String(data.get('google') || ''),
  };

  const remember = data.get('remember') === 'on';
  if (remember) {
    localStorage.setItem(STORAGE_KEY, JSON.stringify(keys));
  } else {
    localStorage.removeItem(STORAGE_KEY);
    // keep `keys` in memory if your app has a state store
  }

  apiKeysDialog.close();

  // TODO: propagate keys to your app’s API client layer
  // e.g., window.appConfig.setApiKeys(keys)
});
```

### Integration point: where keys are used
Wherever you create API clients, read from:
- In-memory state (preferred), falling back to
- `localStorage` (if enabled)

Keep a single “source of truth” function:
```js
export function getApiKey(provider) {
  // 1) in-memory store
  // 2) localStorage fallback
}
```

